occurrences.line_text: The sonnes of Day he fauoureth, I see,
O welcome child, whom I haue longd to see,
And heauenly virgin thus outraged see,
With chaunge of feare, to see the Lyon looke so grim.
Sometimes Dame Venus selfe he seemes to see,
Flocke all about to see her louely face:
Vnto the woods, to see her little sonne;
To see his sire and offspring auncient.
These eyes did see that knight both liuing and eke ded.
To see two knights in trauell on my way
To see their blades so greedily imbrew,
Ah dearest dame (quoth he) how might I see
That none can breath, nor see, nor heare at will,
To see what end of fight should him befall that day.
To see his loued Squire into such thraldome brought.
And threatning high his dreadfull stroke did see,
And he that high does sit, and all things see
With hasty ioy: to see him made her glad,
And of my selfe now mated, as ye see;
And ioyd to see her louer languish and lament.
For leuer had I die, then see his deadly face.
But entred in a spacious court they see,
Strange thing it is an errant knight to see
Thy selfe to see, and tyred limbs to rest,
And greatly ioy each other well to see:
That her to see should be but troublesome.
Then come thou man of earth, and see the way,
As he thereon stood gazing, he might see
For thou emongst those Saints, whom thou doest see,
So came to Vna, who him ioyd to see,
Whom I from far see on the walles appeare
The knight was wrath to see his stroke beguyld,
Behold I see the hauen nigh at hand,
To see the face of that victorious man:
Toung hates to tell the rest, that eye to see abhord.
Great pittie is to see you thus dismaid,
Ne would she speake, ne see, ne yet be seene,
To see faire heauens face, and life not leaue,
And see the saluing of your blotted name.
To see the Redcrosse thus aduaunced hye;
To see sad pageants of mens miseries,
This lucklesse child, whom thus ye see with bloud defild.
Straunge sort of fight, three valiaunt knights to see
Did see and grieue at his bold fashion;
The ends of all their knots, that none might see,
Hayle Groome; didst not thou see a bleeding Hind,
Such wounded beast, as that, I did not see,
There maist thou best be seene, and best maist see:
As one vnfit therefore, that all might see
He saw from farre, or seemed for to see
Ne euer thing, that she could thinke or see,
When I should see, that would me nearer moue,
That on his shield depainted he did see;
That ill beseemes thee, such as I thee see,
Did lightly leape, where he them bound did see,
Whiles Guyon standing by, their vncouth strife does see.
Whom should he, but his owne deare Lord, there see,
To see my Lord so deadly damnifyde
Burning in flames, yet no flames can I see,
To see Pyrrochles there so rudely rage:
And cald, Pyrrochles, what is this, I see?
What flames (quoth he) when I thee present see,
To see his secret store.
Come thou (quoth he) and see. So by and by
As eye of man did neuer see before;
That liuing eye before did neuer see:
Through the dim shade, that all men might it see:
Clothed with leaues, that none the wood mote see
But if that thou be such, as I thee see,
Soone shalt thou see, and then beleeue for troth,
With so fresh hew vprising him to see,
I liue this day, and see my foes subdewd,
That euen heauen reioyced her sweete face to see.
Great wonder had the knight, to see the mayd
Great pleasure had those stranger knights, to see
How oft that day did sad Brunchildis see
He built by art vpon the glassy See
To see a cruell fight doen by the Prince this day.
That through his carkasse one might plainely see:
Like did he neuer heare, like did he neuer see.
They passing by, that griesly mouth did see,
They passing by, a goodly Ship did see,
On th'other side they see that perilous Poole,
Suddeine they see from midst of all the Maine,
Such as Dame Nature selfe mote feare to see,
That is our Selfe, whom though we do not see,
Through guilefull semblaunts, which he makes vs see.
Through euery channell running one might see;
Out of this fountaine, sweet and faire to see,
That through the waues one might the bottom see,
Ah see, who so faire thing doest faine to see,
Ah see, who so faire thing doest faine to see,
Ah see the Virgin Rose, how sweetly shee
That fairer seemes, the lesse ye see her may;
Lo see soone after, how more bold and free
Loe see soone after, how she fades, and falles away.
Nor the fine nets, which oft we wouen see
That certes it great pittie was to see
Was fowly ra'st, that none the signes might see;
And some for wrath, to see their captiue Dame:
Said Guyon, See the mind of beastly man,
Your selfe you couet to see pictured,
In mirrours more then one her selfe to see,
Which outrage when those gentle knights did see,
Ah (said she then) now may ye all see plaine,
Too well we see, (said they) and proue too well
Which stately manner when as they did see,
By knowen signes and passions, which I see,
To trauell, goe to see that dreadfull place:
Thou her afford, full shortly I her dead shall see.
If ay more goodly creature thou didst see;
Their beames shall oft breake forth, that men them faire may see.
Ye see that good king Vther now doth make
Then when I shall my selfe in safety see,
And all the griesly Monsters of the See
Stood gaping at their gate, and wondred them to see.
To see friends graue, the[m] dead the graue selfe to engrosse.
That doest all things deface, ne lettest see
And all that lewdnesse loue, doe hate the light to see.
Wonder it is to see, in diuerse minds,
That euer liuing eye I weene did see;
Else shall thy louing Lord thee see no more,
To succour wretched wights, whom we captiued see.
Ioue laught on Venus from his soueraigne see,
Wondred to see her belly so vpblone,
And euery one did aske, did he him see;
To see so faire things mard, and spoyled quight:
Me seemes I see Amintas wretched fate,
To see his whole yeares labour lost so soone,
Or brutishly brought vp, that neu'r did fashions see.
And grudg'd to see the counterfet should shame
But if thee list to see thy Courser ronne,
As pittying to see her waile and weepe;
That now no more we can the maine-land see,
See how the heauens of voluntary grace,
Was Florimell, when Proteus she did see thereby.
Or speake ye of report, or did ye see
These eyes did see, that they will euer rew
But they dissembled, what they did not see,
The fairest woman wight, that euer eye did see.
But seeing still the more desir'd to see,
False loue, why do men say, thou canst not see,
To see th'vnkindnesse of his Hellenore.
Ne stayes, till safe himselfe he see from ieopardy.
And with her wend, to see what new successe
To see him in his soueraigne maiestee,
She cast her eies, to see what was become
For life she him enuyde, and long'd reuenge to see.
Conceiued had, to see her owne dear knight,
There did he see, that most on earth him ioyd,
Was then assembled, deeds of armes to see:
Her face most fowle and filthy was to see,
So forth he fiercely prickt, that one him scarce could see.
First he desir'd their cause of strife to see:
Glad man was he to see that ioyous sight,
In which you safe I see, whom thousand late,
Come see the secret of the life of man,
That she might see her childre[n]s thrids forth brought,
To see their thrids so thin, as spiders frame,
Which is of them the shortest, as I see,
Yet whilest they liued none did euer see
Did euer see vpon this world to shine,
Was set, to see the fortune of that fray,
Were much amaz'd the headlesse tronke to see
And secret feare, to see their fatall fine,
That so to see him made her heart to quaile:
Wonder it is that sudden change to see:
But Triamond halfe wroth to see him staid,
There might ye see loose steeds at randon ronne,
Then next ensew'd the Paragon to see
So many faire did see, as here he might haue sought.
Yet all were glad there Florimell to see;
Whom when the rest did see her to refuse,
Yet looking round about him none could see;
Weening some heauenly goddesse he did see,
Ioyous to see her safe after long toyle.
I ioy to see you lout so low on ground,
Feared in vaine, sith meanes ye see there wants theretoo.
To tell (quoth she) that which ye see, needs not;
Where hardly eye mote see bright heauens face,
With mild regard, to see his ruefull plight,
To see his foe breath out his spright in vaine:
And howld aloud to see his Lord there slaine,
Amongst the rest she chaunced there to see
For neuer two so like did liuing creature see.
To see the sight perforce, that both her eyes were loth.
So did the other knights and Squires, which him did see.
Such mortall malice, wonder was to see
Aye me to see that gentle maide so tost.
Should happen this with liuing eye to see,
With endlesse cost, to be th'Almighties see;
And then all liuing wights, soone as they see
And almost blind through eld, that scarce her way could see.
And shall see Stamford, though now homely hid,
And ioy likewise this solemne day to see?
Who thither with her came, to learne and see
Though vaine I see my sorrowes to vnfold,
Yet loe the seas I see by often beating,
And mourn'd to see her losse before her eyne,
To see an helpelesse euill, double griefe doth lend.
Mongst those twelue signes, which nightly we doe see
That euer I this dismall day did see:
But his blasphemous head, that all might see,
All which when Artegall did see, and heare,
The sea it selfe doest thou not plainely see
To see the thing, that seem'd so excellent,
And suffred all his secret marke to see:
It's punishment enough, that all his shame doe see.
Two Ilands, which ye there before you see
But see how much her purpose was deceaued.
And wend with me, that ye may see and know,
Rather then see her people spoiled quight,
From time to time, when thou it best shalt see,
That I would hide, will needs, I see, be rad.
By outward signes, (as well he might) did see,
That by your change of cheare is easie for to see.
They doe thy loue, forlorne in womens thraldome see.
That she the face of her new foe might see.
To see her Lord, that was reported drent,
Then farewell fleshly force; I see thy pride is nought.
Who when him selfe now well recur'd did see,
Witnesse the Paynims both, whom ye may see
These two false Knights, whom there ye lying see,
That all men which that spectacle did see,
and see her rich array.
With her, to see her Ladie thence no farre away.
To see her Ladie, as they did agree.
Nigh to the place, which ye desir'd to see:
There shall ye see my souerayne Lady Queene
Straunge there to see, it did them much amaze,
Who sate on high, that she might all men see,
Who when he none of all those knights did see
And that so wretched one, as ye do see
That any yron eyes to see it would agrize.
So that no whit of them remayning one may see.
To see if entrance there as yet obtaine he might.
To see the man, whose euerlasting praise
Sith no redemption nigh she did nor heare nor see.
Which see not perfet things but in a glas:
Sayd Artegall, I such a Beast did see,
Yet but a slender slip, that scarse did see
The knight, as ye did see, on horsebacke was,
Whom when my knight did see so louely faire,
To take me vp (as this young man did see)
Most ioyfull man her sire was her to see,
And eke the Lady was full faire to see,
He laught, and mockt to see him like to swim.
For seldome yet did liuing creature see,
Whom now in deadly daunger he did see;
Vprear'd her head to see that chearefull sight.
Yet now no lesse encombrance she did see,
Which we might see after our selues remaine
That ruth it was to see him so lament.
For pitty so to see him ouerset.
To whom she thus; I am, as now ye see,
Whom Gods doe hate, and heauens abhor to see;
To see him so bedight with bloodie gore,
What meaneth this, which here I see before?
Which ye may see yet all about me steeme.
Did slay againe, as ye may see there in the stound.
Where he himselfe might see his foeman slaine;
The picture of his punishment might see,
That he might see his men, and muster them by oth.
To see her sore lament, and bite her tender lip.
As if it them should grieue to see his punishment.
As loth to see, or to be seene at all:
And to the Prince thus sayd; See you Sir Knight,
See how they doe that Squire beat and reuile;
See how they doe the Lady hale and draw.
Like the faire yuory shining they did see,
And in the midst a Shepheard piping he did see.
There he did see, that pleased much his sight,
Right happy thou, that mayst them freely see:
Or false dissemblaunce all them plaine may see,
Such were those Goddesses, which ye did see;
Who rashly sought that, which I mote not see.
There she beheld, that sore her grieu'd to see,
He sought the woods; but no man could see there;
That euer I did liue, this day to see,
Then here to see all desolate and wast,
Vnto the place, to see what should be donne.
To see the hatefull sunne, that he might tell
To see him leade that Beast in bondage strong,
Reioyced much to see his captiue plight,
And partly female of his fruitfull seed;
The hight of three the tallest sonnes of mortall seed.
Of many Dragonets, his fruitfull seed;
Doth beare the fairest flowre in honorable seed.
Betweene the vulgar and the noble seed,
But sparks, seed, drops, and filth do thus delay;
The sparks soone quench, the springing seed outweed,
And all his seed the curse doth often cleaue,
In all that seemed fit for kingly seed:
The fierce Spumador borne of heauenly seed:
To Elfes, but sprong of seed terrestriall,
The royall seed, the antique Troian blood,
O what auailes it of immortall seed
With heauenly seed, whereof wise Pï¿½on sprong)
Dayes dearest children be the blessed seed,
Whose noble kind at first was sure of heauenly seed.
They both her twins, both borne of heauenly seed,
Liues still: and to this feast with Neptunes seed was dight.
Which as a stocke he left vnto his seede;
The fire of sparkes, the weede of little seede,
Like as the Basiliske of serpents seede,
To all the Sea-gods and their fruitfull seede,
Of th'Oceans seede, but Ioues and Phoebus kinde;
Whose fruitfull seede farre passeth those in land,
Yet then likewise the wicked seede of vice
Like fruitles seede, of which vntimely death should grow.
As thicke as doth the seede after the sowers hand;
The seede of all this euill first doth spring,
Now growen great, at first of little seedes,
The seedes of euill wordes, and factious deedes;
And those same cursed seedes doe also serue
From heauenly seedes of bounty soueraine,
Without regard of good, dyes like ill grounded seeds.
With this faire Mayd, and in her mynde the seeds
She lookt about, and seeing one in mayle
His Ladie seeing all, that chaunst, from farre
The wicked witch now seeing all this while
Till seeing by her side the Lyon stand,
Whom seeing such, for dread he durst not show
The wise Southsayer seeing so sad sight,
Seeing the gored woundes to gape so wyde,
His cruell stepdame seeing what was donne,
They seeing Vna, towards her gan wend,
Where seeing Mercie, that his steps vp bare,
Which as an Eagle, seeing pray appeare,
Who seeing him from farre so fierce to pricke,
That seeing good Sir Guyon, could vneath
The seely man seeing him ryde so rancke,
Who seeing one that shone in armour faire,
Seeing at last her selfe from daunger rid,
Whom Guyon seeing stoup, pursewed fast
The knight him seeing labour so in vaine,
The Palmer seeing his left empty place,
Which seeing stout Bunduca, vp arose,
Till gentle Alma seeing it so late,
Till that the Prince seeing her wofull plight,
The Palmer seeing them in safetie past,
Which seeing good Sir Guyon, deare besought
Her tender babe, it seeing safe appeare,
The doubtfull Mayd, seeing her selfe descryde,
The which his mother seeing, gan to feare
That seeing now the onely last of three,
Which seeing faire Belphoebe, gan to feare,
That his sad mother seeing his sore plight,
And seeing none in place, he gan to make
Who seeing her gan streight vpstart, and thought
He seeing with that Chorle so faire a wight,
Yet seeing nigh him ieopardy extreme,
The knight him seeing fly, had no regard
Malbecco seeing them resolu'd in deed
But seeing still the more desir'd to see,
Which th'old man seeing well, who too long thought
That Cupid selfe it seeing, close did smyle,
And readie seeing him with her to fly,
Malbecco seeing, how his losse did lye,
And seeing him behind a straunger knight,
Which the bold Virgin seeing, gan apply
Ne seeing could her wonder satisfie,
Seeing his worke now wasted deepe engrieued was.
The warlike virgine seeing his so prowd
Till that the rest him seeing lie on ground,
The aged Dame him seeing so enraged,
Seeing so faire indeede, as he did say,
Till seeing her, that Florimell did seme,
Who seeing both bent to so bloudy games,
For seeing it at hand, he swaru'd asyde,
Which Cambell seeing come, was nothing slow
Which th'other seeing, gan his course relent,
Whom he now seeing, her remembred well,
Which Braggadocchio seeing, had no will
Which Cambell seeing, though he could not salue,
Who seeing him come on so furiously,
Which Cambell seeing, much the same enuyde,
But Glauce, seeing all that chaunced there,
Whom seeing flie, she speedily poursewed
He seeing her depart, arose vp light,
Who seeing his sad plight, her tender heart
So she them seeing past the reach of eare,
Yet seeing not how thence he mote remoue,
Seeing her selfe all soly succourlesse,
Till seeing them through suffrance hartned more,
Which seeing Marinell, was sore offended,
Whom seeing fit, and with no crime defilde,
She seeing then her selfe forsaken so,
The Championesse, now seeing night at dore,
They seeing that, let driue at him streight way,
Seeing his honor, which she tendred chiefe,
Who seeing her approch gan forward set,
Who seeing him come still so fiercely on,
Which my liege Lady seeing, thought it best,
Whom seeing all in armour bright as day,
Seeing that sad ensample them before,
Which Burbon seeing, her againe assayd,
But Artegall seeing his cruell deed,
Till Artegall him seeing so to rage,
Who seeing him from farre, with piteous sound
And seeing him so fiercely towardes make,
They from the wall him seeing so aghast,
Who seeing, in what daunger he was plast,
Seeing his face so louely sterne and coy,
After whose death, his brother seeing mee
Seeing his sharpe assault and cruell stoure
Seeing the vgly Monster passing by,
Who seeing one in so great daunger set
But he it seeing, lightly to him lept,
Seeing his royall vsage and array,
And eke his Dame him seeing in such guize,
Where seeing him so lie, he left his steed,
Ne could with seeing satisfie his great desire.
Then looking round about, and seeing nought,
Then one of them him seeing so to sweat,
Now seeing Calidore left all alone,
Which seeing Coridon, who her likewise
For that mishap, yet seeing him to mourne,
And seeing them, for tender pittie wept:
And seeing there, that did him pittie sore,
Seeing her weake and wan, through durance long.
The sober mother seeing such her mood,
But seeing Calidore, away he flew,
And chauffed inly, seeing now no more
And seeing it, much wondred at the sight;
Enforst to seeke some couert nigh at hand,
Does seeke to perce: repining courage yields
To seeke her knight; who subtilly betrayd
To seeke her strayed Champion, if she might attaine.
In wayes vnknowne, her wandring knight to seeke,
Was for to seeke aduenture in strange place,
Him for to seeke, ne euer would forsake,
To seeke his kindred, and the lignage right,
And seeke her spouse, that from her still does fly,
But forth she went, to seeke him far and wide.
To seeke her out with labour, and long tyne,
Nine monethes I seeke in vaine yet ni'll that vow vnbind.
To seeke his loue, and th'other for to fight
That chose the narrow path, or seeke the right:
Then seeke this path, that I to thee presage,
To Faery court thou cam'st to seeke for fame,
Faire sonne of Mars, that seeke with warlike spoile.
To seeke that knight, where him that craftie Squire
For all I seeke, is but to haue redrest
As wont ye knights to seeke aduentures wilde,
And cast to seeke him forth through daunger and great dreed.
To seeke her game: Or as that famous Queene
Would from the right way seeke to draw him wide,
To seeke Occasion, where so she bee:
Madman (said then the Palmer) that does seeke
And euery way did seeke into his life,
So euill thing to seeke vnto their ayd,
And seeke aduentures, as he with Prince Arthur went.
To seeke her louer (loue farre sought alas,)
The greater Britaine, here to seeke for prayse and fame.
The which I seeke to wreake, and Arthegall he hight.
Making her seeke an vnknowne Paramoure,
What meanes shall she out seeke, or what wayes take?
To seeke aduentures, which mote him befall,
Her now I seeke, and if ye vnderstand
Of whom ye seeke to be most magnifide:
To seeke his Lady, where he mote her find;
To seeke for hearbes, that mote him remedy;
Him for to seeke, she left her heauenly hous,
To scorne the ioy, that Ioue is glad to seeke;
And sharply said; Goe Dame, goe seeke your boy,
To seeke the fugitiue, both farre and nere,
Who wandring for to seeke her louer deare,
That raungd abroad to seeke aduentures wilde,
To seeke young men, to quench her flaming thurst,
And seeke else without hazard of thy hed.
And fals to ground, to seeke for succour theare,
He was compeld to seeke some refuge neare,
That who from East to West will endlong seeke,
To seeke her endlong, both by sea and lond.
That seeke a Lady,---There he suddein staid,
To seeke his wife, that was farre wandered:
Who from her went to seeke another lot,
But let vs go to seeke my dearest Dame,
That did not seeke t'appease their deadly hate,
That seeke perforce her from you both to take,
From blouddy strife, and blessed peace to seeke,
Which Ladies ought to loue, and seeke for to obtaine.
To seeke her lou'd, making blind Loue her guide.
Vnluckie Mayd to seeke her enemie!
Vnluckie Mayd to seeke him farre and wide,
That forced them to seeke some couert bowre,
That where ye left, I may her seeke, as doth behoue.
With whom she went to seeke faire Amoret,
To seeke by flight her fellowship t'eschew,
To seeke their loues dispersed diuersly,
Was forst to seeke my lifes deare patronesse:
In generation seeke to quench their inward fire.
But what doe I their names seeke to reherse,
Whereby to seeke some meanes it to appease.
For it was not the right, which he did seeke;
Shapt like a horses shoe, who list to seeke it there.
She goes to seeke him, Dolon meetes
She thought to send some one to seeke him out;
Of errant Knights, to seeke her errant Knight;
